{{Use British English|date=October 2017}} This is a '''list of Lieutenants and Keepers of Hampton Court Chase''' and [[ex officio]] (by virtue of that office) '''Rangers of Bushy Park'''.<ref name=page>'Hampton, introduction', ''A History of the County of Middlesex: Volume 2'', ed. William Page (London, 1911), pp. 319-324. British History Online http://www.british-history.ac.uk/vch/middx/vol2/pp319-324 accessed 1 October 2017.</ref>
==History== {{See also|Chase (land)}} {{Annotated image | image = 1764_Gentleman%27s_Magazine_Map_of_London_and_Environs_-_Geographicus_-_London-gentsmag-1764.jpg | image-width = 2000 <!-- choose any width, as you like it. It doesn't matter the factual width of the image--> | image-left = -150 <!-- crop the left part. Be aware of the "-" minus symbol --> | image-top = -1350 <!-- crop the upper part. Be aware of the "-" minus symbol --> | width = 300 <!-- crop the right part. That will be the width of the image in the article --> | height = 300 <!-- crop the below part. That will be the height of the image in the article --> | float = right | annotations = <!--this parameter must be included --> | caption = Extract from ''Gentleman's Magazine: Map of London & Environs'', 1764 noting the Earl of Halifax owned more than one Gentleman's Houses [mansions] in and adjoining Bushy Park, Hampton and Teddington, Middlesex}} In 1539 Hampton Court Chase was created an 'Honour' by an [[Act of Parliament]] instigated by [[Henry VIII]] and passed as a public act by approval of Parliament and the King. The title holder increasingly over time referred to as '''Ranger''' or '''Keeper of Bushey Park''' held as his domain the right to build and rebuild a grand house in Bushy Park coupled with a degree of local power and exercise likewise to the monarch in hunting rights.<ref name=page/> Henry thereby created the first forest since the [[New Forest]] of William the Conqueror and obtained the rights to a share of cattle and game in the extent to append to his "close park" to Hampton Court Palace taken from [[Cardinal Wolsey|Wolsey]]. The area's other local landowners included principally manorial tenants of the [[Dissolution of the Monasteries|confiscated]] [[Chertsey Abbey|Chertsey]] and [[Westminster Abbey]]s &ndash; and made all non-[[Chase (land)|mete]] parts an overall chase for royal and official hunting parties for [[wild boar|boar]], game birds, [[hare]], [[Rabbit|coneys]] and deer.<ref name=ecook/>{{refn|group=n|In the era in which the Chase was founded many private land interests 'escheated to' (owners failed to pay a relief to effect [[livery of seisin]] after [[inquisitions post mortem]]); 'were surrendered to' (were purchased by); or were forfeited by attainder/were among attainted estates (see [[attainder]]) to the Crown (monarch).}} Holding all persons to account for animal grazing and wood-taking financially were added benefits.<ref name=ecook/> The statute set up a new forest or chase for the king, to be called 'Hampton Court Chase' but which was smaller than the many square miles the King wished:{{quote|But it plainly appeareth both by the kings...indenture [...of first October 1537...(legal deed)], and by the judgement of the whole parliament that the king could neither erect any chase or forest over any mans grounds without their consent and agreement.|Sir [[Edward Coke]], Fourth Part: [[Institutes of the Lawes of England]] published 1644|<ref name=ecook> [http://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=File%3AEdward_Coke%2C_The_Fourth_Part_of_the_Institutes_of_the_Laws_of_England_(1st_ed%2C_1644).pdf&page=325 Fourth Part] of the [[Institutes of the Lawes of England]], Sir [[Edward Coke]], 1644, Page 301 (at p. 325 in digitised format) recited verbatim in a 1797 summary of laws [https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=ulE0AAAAIAAJ&vq=hampton%20court%20chase&pg=PA301#v=onepage&q=plainly%20appeareth&f=false here]</ref>}}
The bounds of the chase apart from Bushy Park took in the manors of [[Hampton, London|Hampton]], [[Hanworth]], [[Kempton Park, Surrey|Kempton]], [[Walton-on-Thames]]. Parliament, through the courts, was deemed to have strongly curtailed its royal forest rights so as not to impinge on freeholds nor main customary tenants lands in [[Molesey]], [[Weybridge]], [[Cobham, Surrey|Cobham]] and part of [[Esher]], its furthest reach due to Henry's legal deed (indenture) of 1537.<ref name=ecook/>
The Ranger or Keeper in early years held the position of '''Housekeeper of the [[Hampton Court Palace|Palace]]'''. The rangership of the land in the bend of the river east of the Palace, the 'House' or 'Home' Park was usually separate.<ref name=page/> [[Christopher Villiers, 1st Earl of Anglesey|Kit Villiers]], an ennobled courtier by James I, inherited the honour from his brother and took as his official seat Ashley House (and [[Ashley Park]]) in [[Walton on Thames]]. Reinstatement in wealth and titles to the Villiers (Earls of Jersey and Anglesey) family after the [[English Civil War]] failed to reunite the more southerly lands associated with the honour which were taken and sold in the course of the 1649-1660 [[Commonwealth of England]].<ref>{{cite web|title=Parishes: Walton on Thames, A History of the County of Surrey: Volume 3 |year=1911|pages= 467–475|url= http://www.british-history.ac.uk/report.aspx?compid=43009 |accessdate= 27 July 2014}}</ref> Some holders of the title lived in Bushy Park seasonally or as their main home. The monarch tended to grant the title to the main heir of the previous holder. Parliament in the English Interregnum granted the title to General Monck, who remained in favour in the [[English Restoration]].
